<br>
Ok, sure gating MoBs are a bad thing, even more so if they get away, but the truth is, not all MoBs are casters, and not all gate.<br>
<br>
Again, these spells are designed for the same people the bane spells were invented for. The High End players. It'll be nice to have a 'chance' to stop some of the unstunnable MoBs from gating, but there are so few of them in the game under 50 that coming up with a whole line of spells just devoted to those encounters tells me those encounters were too hard to begin with.<br>
<br>
I've stated in my past posts regarding the fixes we've gotten so far being specific fixes for specific things, but this is crazy.<br>
<br>
So, with what I know now about the &quot;improvements&quot; just over the horizon, here's how I would fix them before they try to release them to us.<br>
<br>
It appears they will be three different spells with three different resistance checks. Why do this? So the Mob has a chance against resisting each &quot;Anti-Gate Debuff&quot; on its rolls.<br>
<br>
They make them stack so you could have three wizards casting a 33% chance at nullifying a MoB gate so it requires three wizards to make them work correctly. Meaning you need more Wizards in your group, more than just one. Three being the magic number.<br>
<br>
Three wizards in one group will destroy just about every normal MoB they come accross. That right there gives players the chance to see what wizards really are capable of. Unfortunately Most players don't want to group with Wizards, and they would much rather just have one in the group and give the other two spots to other classes, making the group more flexible. Forcing a group to have three wizards for 5% of the encounters in the game just to keep them from gating is just plain silly.<br>
How they're making it require 3 different wizard to make it work is interesting. It sounds like they're making it three different spells that will not stack with each other when casted by the same wizard. But if there are three Wizards, then they will stack. Kind of interesting, considering they told Necromancers they couldn't do this (for their DoTs).<br>
<br>
Now, if these spells did something like, a 33% chance at <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  silencing</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> the MoBs, wizards would be praising Lawrence Poe. In that mode, three wizards would be needed to have three chances at 33% chance of silencing a MoB from casting ANY spells. Yes, Lawrence Poe would be getting Christmas cards from me.<br>
<br>
Think about this:<br>
<br>
As the spells are described now, there are three. Each are based off a different resistance check, most likely Fire, Cold, and Magic.<br>
<br>
So at level 51, lets say you get &quot;Gate Crashing: Fire&quot;. This would give you a 33% chance at interrupting the MoBs gate spell.<br>
At level 55 say, you get the next in the series; &quot;Gate Crashing: Cold&quot;. Since you can't cast both of these spells yourself (they overwrite each other if casted by the same player) you need a second wizard to improve your odds of &quot;Anchoring the Mob&quot;. These spells stack, but they don't give you a single 66% chance at &quot;Anchoring&quot; the MoB. They give you two chances at 33% each of &quot;Anchoring&quot; the MoB.<br>
Then at say, level 59, you get &quot;Gate Crashing: Magic&quot;. Once again, it's only useful when stacked with other wizards casting the other gate crashing line. With this third version being cast, you'll have three chances at 33% of causing the MoB to not gate.<br>
<br>
In otherwords:<br>
<br>
It takes 3 spells to make most any mob not gate. Each of them are on a different resistance, so each has a chance to be resisted right away.<br>
Because of the way these spells are being coded, you can't cast all three spells yourself. They don't stack with each other when cast by the same player. So you need two other wizards to cast one of each of the spells.<br>
Lets say each spell gives you a 33% chance at crashing the targets gate spell. It doesn't mean if you have three wizards casting each in the line, that you'll have a 99% of the MoBs gate spell not working. You actually have three chances at 33%. There is a big difference.<br>
<br>
Now, if they'd change the &quot;Gate Crashing&quot; to &quot;Silencing&quot; (The MoB not being able to cast at all) I think Wizards would be VERY pleased. It wouldn't be overpowering due to the fact of the three different castings by three different wizards. It would also have three chances at being resisted, and Three chances at not working for each spell the MoB wants to cast.<br>
<br>
In otherwords:<br>
You have 3 wizards in your group. The Main Tank pulls a casting MoB. The Three wizards would cast their three different versions of this spell. Throughout the fight, in order for the MoB to cast any spells of those types of resistances (Fire, Cold, Magic) they would have to roll higher than a 33. If they rolled lower, they couldn't cast that spell at that time. If they rolled higher, the spell would go off as normal.<br>
<br>
So if you have a creature that casts Ice Comet, you could cast &quot;Silence: Cold&quot; and have a 33% chance of interrupting each time they try to cast Ice Comet.<br>
<br>
Tell me this wouldn't make you drool?<br>
